      <!-- Subjective Section -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="61150-9" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1" codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Subjective" />
          <title>Subjective</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>
              Linda Chen is a 35-year-old female referred for physical therapy for
              management of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD, K21.0) and associated
              musculoskeletal findings including postural dysfunction contributing to
              increased abdominal pressure and symptom exacerbation.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph>
              Patient reports persistent heartburn (6/10 severity), regurgitation after meals,
              and mid-thoracic back pain (4/10) which she attributes to prolonged seated posture
              at her desk job. Symptoms worsen with bending, heavy lifting, and lying flat.
              Currently on pantoprazole 40 mg daily with partial relief.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph>
              Patient denies dysphagia, odynophagia, hematemesis, or unintentional weight loss.
              No prior surgical history. BMI 22.1. Non-smoker, alcohol use: occasional.
            </paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

      <!-- Objective / Physical Findings -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="61149-1" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1" codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Objective" />
          <title>Objective — Physical Therapy Assessment</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph><content styleCode="Bold">Posture Assessment:</content>
              Forward head posture (+3 cm anterior translation), rounded shoulders,
              increased thoracic kyphosis. Lumbar lordosis flattened in sitting.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph><content styleCode="Bold">Range of Motion — Thoracic Spine:</content>
              Flexion 40° (normal 45°), Extension 20° (normal 25°),
              Lateral Flexion L/R: 25°/25° (normal 25°/25°).
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph><content styleCode="Bold">Diaphragmatic Breathing:</content>
              Paradoxical breathing pattern noted on initial assessment.
              Shallow thoracic breathing at rest. Limited diaphragmatic excursion.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph><content styleCode="Bold">Core Strength (MMT):</content>
              Transverse abdominis 3+/5. Multifidus 4/5 bilateral.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph><content styleCode="Bold">Functional Tests:</content>
              Symptom provocation with Valsalva maneuver. Forward bending reproduces
              heartburn within 30 seconds.
            </paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

      <!-- Assessment and Plan -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <templateId root="2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.2.9" extension="2014-06-09" />
          <code code="51847-2" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1" codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Evaluation + Plan note" />
          <title>Assessment and Plan</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>
              <content styleCode="Bold">Diagnosis:</content>
              GERD (K21.0) with contributing postural dysfunction and diaphragmatic dysfunction.
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph>
              <content styleCode="Bold">Physical Therapy Goals (6-week plan):</content>
            </paragraph>
            <list>
              <item>Improve diaphragmatic breathing mechanics to reduce intra-abdominal pressure.</item>
              <item>Correct forward head posture and thoracic kyphosis.</item>
              <item>Strengthen core musculature (transverse abdominis, multifidus).</item>
              <item>Patient education on ergonomics and meal timing.</item>
              <item>Target: 50% reduction in GERD symptom frequency within 6 weeks.</item>
            </list>
            <paragraph>
              <content styleCode="Bold">Treatment This Session:</content>
              Diaphragmatic breathing retraining (20 min). Postural correction exercises:
              thoracic extension over foam roller (3x10). Chin tucks (3x15).
              Manual therapy: thoracic spine joint mobilization grades I-II.
              Patient education: eating posture, meal-to-bed interval (&gt;3 hours).
            </paragraph>
            <paragraph>
              <content styleCode="Bold">Plan:</content>
              PT 2x/week x 6 weeks. Coordinate with referring provider Dr. Rodriguez.
              Re-evaluate in 3 weeks for progress toward goals.
            </paragraph>
          </text>
